WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.160 --> 00:00:04.970
&gt;&gt; Speaker 1: From the Library
of Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:16.020 --> 00:00:17.980
&gt;&gt; Michael North: Hello
everyone and welcome

00:00:17.980 --> 00:00:20.580
to the Lessing J. Rosenwald
Room in the Rare Book

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:25.870
and Special Collections Division
of the Library of Congress.

00:00:25.870 --> 00:00:27.780
Thank you for coming to
this month's Thursday

00:00:27.780 --> 00:00:29.520
Afternoon Lecture.

00:00:29.520 --> 00:00:31.070
My name is Michael
North and I'm head

00:00:31.070 --> 00:00:34.560
of the Rare Book Reading room,
which is right across the hall.

00:00:34.560 --> 00:00:38.210
Today I am pleased to
introduce Elise Friedland,

00:00:38.210 --> 00:00:41.570
who is Associate Professor
of Classics and Art History

00:00:41.570 --> 00:00:44.370
in the Department of Classical
and Near Eastern Languages

00:00:44.370 --> 00:00:48.170
and Civilizations at the George
Washington University here

00:00:48.170 --> 00:00:52.150
in Washington D.C. She
holds a B.A. in Classics

00:00:52.150 --> 00:00:56.310
from Williams College and a
M.A. and Ph.D. in Classical Art

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.360
and Archeology from
the University

00:00:58.360 --> 00:01:00.770
of Michigan in Ann Arbor.

00:01:00.770 --> 00:01:05.280
Professor Friedland specializes
in Roman Marble Sculpture

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:09.270
that was imported and displayed
in the Ancient Near East

00:01:09.270 --> 00:01:12.920
and she has published two
co-edited volumes on the topic,

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:15.860
The Sculptural Environment
of the Roman Near East:

00:01:15.860 --> 00:01:20.840
Reflections on Culture,
Ideology, and Power in 2008

00:01:20.840 --> 00:01:24.200
and the Oxford Handbook
of Roman Sculpture in 2015

00:01:24.200 --> 00:01:27.770
by Oxford University Press
as well as a monograph,

00:01:27.770 --> 00:01:31.640
The The Roman Marble Sculptures
From the Sanctuary of Pan

00:01:31.640 --> 00:01:37.670
at Caesarea, Philippi/Panias
in Israel in 2012.

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:41.170
Her current research, which
investigates American adoptions

00:01:41.170 --> 00:01:43.960
and adaptations of
classical motifs grows

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:45.480
out of a course she developed

00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:49.090
for George Washington University
entitled Greece and Rome

00:01:49.090 --> 00:01:52.540
in Washington D.C.:
Classical Influences

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:54.660
on our Founding Fathers.

00:01:54.660 --> 00:02:00.030
In the fall of 2017 Professor
Friedland was granted a U.S.

00:02:00.030 --> 00:02:02.690
Capitol Historical
Society Fellowship

00:02:02.690 --> 00:02:10.150
to study Constantino Brumidi
Pompeiian style 19th century

00:02:10.150 --> 00:02:14.860
fresco cycle in the Senate
Appropriations Committee Room,

00:02:14.860 --> 00:02:18.990
S127, in the Senate wing of
the U.S. Capitol Building.

00:02:18.990 --> 00:02:20.790
Please welcome her.

00:02:20.790 --> 00:02:26.830
[ Applause ]

