00:03:42.520 --> 00:03:45.100
So starting with
Michael North here,

00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:51.130
who retrieved these giant books
from Fort Meade on my behalf,

00:03:51.130 --> 00:03:56.600
and then Stephanie Stillo and
Jeff Flannery, Barbara Natanson

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:01.040
in prints and photographs,
Cheryl Fox the archivist here,

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:07.910
Michelle Krowl, who you'll see
helped me with Megs journal,

00:04:07.910 --> 00:04:12.120
John Cole, the historian,
and Jan McElvey.

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:16.960
So it's been a fabulous
experience conducting research

00:04:16.960 --> 00:04:20.180
here but it's taken quite
a lineup of specialists

00:04:20.180 --> 00:04:22.420
and experts to support me

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:25.540
and I'm incredibly
thankful to everyone.

00:04:25.540 --> 00:04:31.160
As Michael said, I don't usually
deal with books, rare books,

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:35.000
because we don't have any
more of those from when I work

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:36.300
and where I usually live.

00:04:36.300 --> 00:04:38.290
I usually live in
the Roman world

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:42.170
because I'm a Roman sculpture
specialist and, in particular,

00:04:42.170 --> 00:04:46.210
I work in the Ancient Near
East, in Israel and Jordan.

00:04:46.210 --> 00:04:49.080
So you can just see
what I'm doing there.

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.500
So your question is probably
what are you doing talking

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:57.310
about 19th century painting
and 19th century publications.

00:04:57.310 --> 00:05:00.430
Well, as Michael
pointed out, when I moved

00:05:00.430 --> 00:05:04.710
to GW exactly ten years ago, I
developed a course called Greece

00:05:04.710 --> 00:05:07.300
and Rome in Washington
D.C.: Classical Influences

00:05:07.300 --> 00:05:09.000
on Our Founding Fathers.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.460
And as part of that class
I called up the curator

00:05:12.460 --> 00:05:14.910
of the Capitol and asked if
she would give my class a tour

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:16.610
and that was Barbara Wolanin.

00:05:16.610 --> 00:05:18.770
And she took us all
around the Capitol

00:05:18.770 --> 00:05:20.070
and showed us architecture

00:05:20.070 --> 00:05:22.900
but she also showed
us some painting.

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:28.230
This famous fresco on the
underside of the Rotunda

00:05:28.230 --> 00:05:30.220
by Constantino Brumidi, right?

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:32.840
The Apotheosis of
George Washington.

00:05:32.840 --> 00:05:36.400
And then she took
us into another,

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:39.510
she took us into the Senate
corridors and this room, S127.

00:05:39.510 --> 00:05:41.480
And we were there for
about ten minutes.

00:05:41.480 --> 00:05:44.520
And when we came out
I said to her, "Whoa.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:46.950
There's a lot going
on in that room."

00:05:46.950 --> 00:05:48.490
And she said, "Yes!

00:05:48.490 --> 00:05:52.430
And no one has ever studied
it before completely.

00:05:52.430 --> 00:05:57.840
Would you like to do that?"

00:05:57.840 --> 00:06:04.940
And I thought to myself, dude,
that is after Constantine.

00:06:04.940 --> 00:06:17.910
My world ends in 324
A.D. I am not responsible

00:06:17.910 --> 00:06:21.690
for anything after Constantine.

00:06:21.690 --> 00:06:24.380
And besides, that's
painting, I do sculpture.

00:06:24.380 --> 00:06:27.250
So in my head I had this whole
dialogue and I said, "Oh,

00:06:27.250 --> 00:06:28.810
that's an interesting thought."

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:30.640
And then I moved on.

00:06:30.640 --> 00:06:33.390
Three years later I'm
teaching the class again,

00:06:33.390 --> 00:06:37.180
I try to email Barbara to
get a tour, no response.

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.520
I call the office, Vickie
answers and says, "Oh,

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:45.230
I'm sure the new Curator
of the Capitol would

00:06:45.230 --> 00:06:47.700
like to give you a tour."

00:06:47.700 --> 00:06:51.940
And so then I met Michelle and
she took our class in there

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:55.470
for 45 minutes and while she
was talking to my students

00:06:55.470 --> 00:07:00.540
about Brumidi finally got
a look at that room, S127.

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:07.420
It was originally made for
the Naval Affairs Committee

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:10.270
and today is the Senate
Appropriations Committee

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:11.570
Meeting Room.

00:07:11.570 --> 00:07:13.820
And we had this fabulous
exchange

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:19.980
about some things I was seeing
in the room and she said,

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:24.980
"You know, I really think you
should work on this room."

00:07:24.980 --> 00:07:32.050
She had no idea what Barbara
had said and so then I thought,

00:07:32.050 --> 00:07:34.260
okay, that's two Curators
of the Capitol in the space

00:07:34.260 --> 00:07:40.940
of three years, somebody is
trying to tell me something.

00:07:40.940 --> 00:07:43.010
And the rest is history.

00:07:43.010 --> 00:07:47.220
Right? So here is the room
that we are talking about.

00:07:47.220 --> 00:07:48.580
This is S127.

00:07:48.580 --> 00:07:51.050
Today this is the Senate
Appropriations Committee

00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:52.350
Meeting Room.

00:07:52.350 --> 00:07:54.140
But originally, as I said,

00:07:54.140 --> 00:07:58.140
it was made to house the Naval
Affairs Committee, right,

00:07:58.140 --> 00:08:10.380
and it did that from
about 1860 until 1897.

00:08:10.380 --> 00:08:15.550
Then it housed a variety
of different committees

00:08:15.550 --> 00:08:19.260
until it became the Senate
Appropriations Committee Meeting

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:22.390
Room in 1912.

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:26.610
This room is pretty important
in terms of its decoration

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:30.230
because it is the first
full-scale commission done

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:34.080
by Constantino Brumidi,
right, the guy who was famous

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:37.720
for the Apotheosis right here.

00:08:37.720 --> 00:08:44.270
This is actually his first
full-scale commission.

00:08:44.270 --> 00:08:48.120
And it is pretty
different than many

00:08:48.120 --> 00:08:51.510
of his other painted
rooms in the Senate wing.

00:08:51.510 --> 00:08:56.480
Why? Because if you look at
it, for example, in comparison

00:08:56.480 --> 00:08:58.530
to the Senate Reception Room,
it is much more coherent,

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:03.370
this Naval Affairs Committee
Meeting room is much more

00:09:03.370 --> 00:09:05.630
coherent in terms of
its style so this tends

00:09:05.630 --> 00:09:09.480
to mix a variety of
different styles.

00:09:09.480 --> 00:09:15.150
It is also much more coherent in
terms of its narrative program,

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:17.130
what is the story it's trying
to tell through the paintings.

00:09:17.130 --> 00:09:19.800
So, this is a pretty important
first thing by Brumidi

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:21.520
in the Capitol to study.

00:09:21.520 --> 00:09:24.650
And, in fact, I want to give
you a little bit of background

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:25.950
about our artist, Brumidi.

00:09:25.950 --> 00:09:27.660
He was actually Italian, right?

00:09:27.660 --> 00:09:30.050
so he was born in
Rome and he went

00:09:30.050 --> 00:09:31.930
to a very famous
art academy there,

00:09:31.930 --> 00:09:34.240
the Academy di San Luca and,
unfortunately, he got caught

00:09:34.240 --> 00:09:35.540
up in the Italian
Revolution and sort

00:09:35.540 --> 00:09:36.840
of became a political refugee,

00:09:36.840 --> 00:09:38.140
such that in 1952 he came
to the United States.

00:09:38.140 --> 00:09:39.440
And he was here because
he had commissions

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:40.740
in churches in New York.

00:09:40.740 --> 00:09:42.040
He also painted in
Philadelphia, Baltimore,

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:43.340
Havana, and even Mexico City.

00:09:43.340 --> 00:09:44.640
And at one point he was on
his way, at one point in 1854,

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:45.940
I think, he was on his way back
from Mexico City to New York,

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:47.240
his sort of home base when
he met Montgomery Meigs,

00:09:47.240 --> 00:09:48.540
who had been hired as the
engineer of the Capitol

00:09:48.540 --> 00:09:49.840
to complete the construction,
and the believed,

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:51.140
decoration of the
Capitol Building.

00:09:51.140 --> 00:09:52.440
And so Meigs, it was perfect
timing because Meigs was looking

00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:53.740
for someone who could
decorate the interior

00:09:53.740 --> 00:09:55.040
of the Capitol Building with
elaborate, Roman style frescoes

00:09:55.040 --> 00:09:56.340
and he was having a dreadful
time finding any American

00:09:56.340 --> 00:09:57.640
painter who was able
to fit that bill.

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:58.940
And along came Constantine
Brumidi.

00:09:58.940 --> 00:10:03.060
So he, Meigs hired Brumidi
to do a little test panel

00:10:03.060 --> 00:10:08.030
on the House side apparently
the Senators were very favorable

00:10:08.030 --> 00:10:09.330
about it.

00:10:09.330 --> 00:10:11.060
Meigs liked it and
the rest is history.

00:10:11.060 --> 00:10:15.340
He hired Constantino Brumidi,
who is today sometimes known

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:17.200
as the Michelangelo
of the Capitol

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:20.040
or the artist of the Capitol.

00:10:20.040 --> 00:10:23.860
Now, what I wanted to do is
give you a quick orientation

00:10:23.860 --> 00:10:27.640
to the room because then I want
to get to well why are you here

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:30.120
in the Library of Congress,
like what does this got to do,

00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:32.780
why shouldn't we be in the
Capitol Building right now.

00:10:32.780 --> 00:10:36.100
So let me just sort of give you
a quick visual tour of the room

00:10:36.100 --> 00:10:39.830
and then I will explain
what we're doing here.

00:10:39.830 --> 00:10:44.000
So this is the room from
another angle and you can see

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:45.570
that the decorative program,

00:10:45.570 --> 00:10:49.150
the fresco cycle involves
sort of four main areas.

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:52.070
It involves the walls, right?

00:10:52.070 --> 00:10:56.800
So there are nine of these
sort of solid background panels

00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:58.410
with floating maidens in them

00:10:58.410 --> 00:11:01.330
and then it involves
these lunettes.

00:11:01.330 --> 00:11:03.050
I'm actually just go like this.

00:11:03.050 --> 00:11:06.740
So there are nine of these kinds
of panels and then the lunettes

00:11:06.740 --> 00:11:09.840
over them that, today, have
architectural scenes in them.

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:12.510
They were originally meant
to have famous naval battles

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:14.780
from American history in them.

00:11:14.780 --> 00:11:17.950
There are two bays in the room,
actually I'm going to back

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:19.250
up just so you can see that.

00:11:19.250 --> 00:11:22.920
Can you see that there's one bay
here and then another bay here?

00:11:22.920 --> 00:11:29.500
And on these bays there are sort
of four areas that have niches

00:11:29.500 --> 00:11:34.090
in them and each niche is filled
with its own marine deity right?

00:11:34.090 --> 00:11:37.380
Because you're in the Naval
Affairs Committee Meeting Room.

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:40.280
So, you know, you can
see there's Neptune

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:44.530
and we have Amphitrite,
and we have Aeolus.

00:11:44.530 --> 00:11:48.220
So there's one who is
the Goddess America

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:50.350
so she's a little aberration.

00:11:50.350 --> 00:11:56.090
But anyway, and each deity is
in a niche and then flanked

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:58.150
by two attendants, right?

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:01.640
And then finally,
there are these bands,

00:12:01.640 --> 00:12:02.940
there are three bands.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:05.200
One up here, there's one
in the center of the room,

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:06.500
and there's one on the
other side of the room.

00:12:06.500 --> 00:12:10.680
So that is Brumidi's
decorative scheme for this room.

00:12:10.680 --> 00:12:15.160
Now, it was known to the former
Curator of the Capitol, I mean,

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:19.470
this room obviously looks
very Roman in style, right?

00:12:19.470 --> 00:12:21.750
But, in fact, the former Curator

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:26.470
of the Capitol had identified
one part of this room

00:12:26.470 --> 00:12:30.950
that seemed to be a dead ringer
for or was definitely based

00:12:30.950 --> 00:12:33.870
on an actual painting
from Pompeii.

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:35.430
And so you can see
that right here.

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:36.960
I'm just going to test this
but I know [inaudible].

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:41.520
The pointer doesn't
work on this,

00:12:41.520 --> 00:12:42.950
you need a reflective surface.

00:12:42.950 --> 00:12:45.660
Anyway, so this is a floating
[inaudible] right here

00:12:45.660 --> 00:12:51.780
and if we look she is
actually based on this fresco,

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:56.030
this Roman wall painting,
that is from the House

00:12:56.030 --> 00:12:58.600
of the Ship at Pompeii, okay?

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:02.500
And her question was, the reason
she had approached me was she

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:06.110
wanted to know were there
other matches in the room

00:13:06.110 --> 00:13:08.670
or did Brumidi sort of
start with this and kind

00:13:08.670 --> 00:13:11.550
of make the rest of
the room up, right?

00:13:11.550 --> 00:13:13.750
So that was the big
question and that's sort

00:13:13.750 --> 00:13:18.100
of why Barbara Wolanin and
Michelle Cohen hired me

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:20.950
to study this room, right?

00:13:20.950 --> 00:13:26.190
And I began in August
of 2017 and I kind

00:13:26.190 --> 00:13:29.570
of was getting panicked
by early October

00:13:29.570 --> 00:13:32.920
because I wasn't
finding any other matches

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:35.110
and I started getting
really nervous that a bunch

00:13:35.110 --> 00:13:37.870
of people are going to be
very disappointed in me

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:41.180
and then I realized,
let's think about this.

00:13:41.180 --> 00:13:43.790
Naval Affairs Committee
Meeting Room,

00:13:43.790 --> 00:13:45.400
this is from the
House of the Ship.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:49.520
I wonder if Brumidi had some
publication of the House

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:53.430
of the Ship and took a bunch
of other figures from that

00:13:53.430 --> 00:13:54.730
and altered them, right?

00:13:54.730 --> 00:13:58.890
But then I couldn't find
any publication of the House

00:13:58.890 --> 00:14:04.470
of the Ship but I did
find this drawing,

00:14:04.470 --> 00:14:07.740
which is in Volume
One right over there.

00:14:07.740 --> 00:14:14.120
Okay? And it turns out that this
is the only complete drawing

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:22.560
of the entire wall in which are
floating maenad figures, okay?

00:14:22.560 --> 00:14:27.120
It is very common to see just
this floating maenad reproduced

00:14:27.120 --> 00:14:31.000
in several publications
from the early 19th century

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.650
of wall paintings from Pompeii.

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:37.460
But this is the only complete
drawing of the entire wall,

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:41.270
which was the south wall of
a dining room in this House

00:14:41.270 --> 00:14:43.730
of the Ship, the
Casa de Naviglio.

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:47.880
And it turns out
that this drawing is

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:54.120
from the very important
publication by Wilhelm Zahn,

00:14:54.120 --> 00:15:00.170
the most beautiful ornaments and
the most fancy wall paintings

00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:01.760
from Pompeii [inaudible], okay?

00:15:01.760 --> 00:15:06.960
And as I was looking at
this drawing and saying yes,

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:11.840
there's are maenad, I
started realizing, hold on.

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:17.130
I recognize other things
like these columns, right?

00:15:17.130 --> 00:15:19.290
So, oops, sorry, so there's
our floating in maenad, right?

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:24.170
You can see, but I also
recognized those columns

00:15:25.670 --> 00:15:27.870
and then I realized
that it turns

00:15:27.870 --> 00:15:32.970
out that Constantino Brumidi
based his entire design

00:15:32.970 --> 00:15:35.910
of the room on this one drawing.

00:15:35.910 --> 00:15:41.650
So you can see that he not
only adopts flanking floating

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:44.900
maenads, he turns
them into maidens,

00:15:44.900 --> 00:15:47.770
but he's got the
flanking columns

00:15:47.770 --> 00:15:51.280
and the secondary scene got
turned into a doorway, right?

00:15:51.280 --> 00:15:54.650
So less work for him creating
complex figural scenes.

00:15:54.650 --> 00:15:58.690
Not that he couldn't take that
on, he was fabulous, right?

00:15:58.690 --> 00:16:01.540
And, in fact, this
scheme, the design scheme

00:16:01.540 --> 00:16:05.560
for the walls goes even
further because you can see

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:09.250
that the wall in the
Pompeiian dining room had this

00:16:09.250 --> 00:16:10.950
vegetal border.

00:16:10.950 --> 00:16:13.970
Well, we have that here,
a version by Brumidi.

00:16:13.970 --> 00:16:18.250
It was originally topped by
some fantastic creatures;

00:16:18.250 --> 00:16:23.180
they got turned into swans
and it had some vegetal motifs

00:16:23.180 --> 00:16:25.370
in the lower corner
and those got turned

00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:27.650
into cornucopia by Brumidi.

00:16:27.650 --> 00:16:31.730
So he really did look
very carefully at this

00:16:31.730 --> 00:16:36.030
and match what he
was doing one to one.

00:16:36.030 --> 00:16:42.300
So the question for me was
then okay, I began to read

00:16:42.300 --> 00:16:45.530
about this book by
Wilhelm Zahn and I realized

00:16:45.530 --> 00:16:50.340
that this was a big, large,
fancy, expensive book.

00:16:50.340 --> 00:16:54.170
It is not something that a
political refugee is going

00:16:54.170 --> 00:16:58.910
to be carrying from Italy
across the ocean with him.

00:16:58.910 --> 00:17:01.310
So I thought, how did
he have access for this

00:17:01.310 --> 00:17:02.610
and what is this book.

00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:05.580
The other thing that struck
me was that, you know,

00:17:05.580 --> 00:17:08.990
I teach a course on Pompeii
and I do a little part of that

00:17:08.990 --> 00:17:12.090
on the history of Pompeii
and the transmission

00:17:12.090 --> 00:17:15.400
of Pompeiian art, you
know, the dissemination

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:16.850
of the images and things.

00:17:16.850 --> 00:17:20.830
And I thought why have I
never heard of Wilhelm Zahn?

00:17:20.830 --> 00:17:23.620
I mean, I know William Gell,
I know Francois [inaudible].

00:17:23.620 --> 00:17:25.780
I know all these
characters, I'll introduce you

00:17:25.780 --> 00:17:27.270
to them in a little bit.

00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:28.690
I'd never heard of Wilhelm Zahn.

00:17:28.690 --> 00:17:33.060
And I started asking some of my
colleagues, oh, Wilhelm Zahn?

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:37.370
And they'd say, yeah, I've
never really heard of him.

00:17:37.370 --> 00:17:38.840
And I thought well that's weird

00:17:38.840 --> 00:17:40.580
because Brumidi has
heard of him.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:44.350
And where is his book because
I also had spoken with somebody

00:17:44.350 --> 00:17:47.510
that I got connected to through
the U.S. Capitol Historical

00:17:47.510 --> 00:17:52.980
Society, who is a painter
who does historical paintings

00:17:52.980 --> 00:17:55.210
of D.C. and I said, "So,

00:17:55.210 --> 00:17:58.020
could Brumidi have done
this from his head?"

00:17:58.020 --> 00:17:59.780
And he said, "Absolutely not.

00:17:59.780 --> 00:18:01.940
He would've needed a
model to design something

00:18:01.940 --> 00:18:04.740
that complex, absolutely not."

00:18:04.740 --> 00:18:06.410
So I decided to start looking

00:18:06.410 --> 00:18:08.410
around where could
I find this book

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:11.630
and I thought did the Library
of Congress own this book.

00:18:11.630 --> 00:18:15.970
And that's why we're here today
because I ended up getting

00:18:15.970 --> 00:18:19.800
in touch with Michael
North and I said, "Look,

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.270
in your catalogue it says
you have these books,

00:18:22.270 --> 00:18:23.570
could I see them?"

00:18:23.570 --> 00:18:28.160
And he heroically got them from
Fort Meade where they've been

00:18:28.160 --> 00:18:32.170
in storage for goodness
knows how long and behold,

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:36.830
I was able to find
tons more matches.

00:18:36.830 --> 00:18:40.040
So these columns here that
Brumidi painted in the room,

00:18:40.040 --> 00:18:43.320
you can see that this
lower part comes directly

00:18:43.320 --> 00:18:45.460
from this drawing
by Zahn, right?

00:18:45.460 --> 00:18:47.760
On plate 16 and we're
going to watch

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:53.230
because another part he also
takes from the same place, okay?

00:18:53.230 --> 00:18:56.020
So not only does he base
architectural features,

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:59.390
he also has an individual
drawing

00:18:59.390 --> 00:19:02.930
of just his favorite
floating maenad

00:19:02.930 --> 00:19:06.260
and there are other floating
figures that match as well.

00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:10.660
So she was a victory
goddess, carrying a trophy.

00:19:10.660 --> 00:19:14.300
So you just, you know, lose
the wings and change the trophy

00:19:14.300 --> 00:19:18.500
into a pennant and you've got to
put clothes on all these people

00:19:18.500 --> 00:19:19.970
in 19th century America.

00:19:19.970 --> 00:19:23.290
And there you have
another floating figure.

00:19:23.290 --> 00:19:26.070
Some of the attendants
also come directly

00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:28.900
from Wilhelm Zahn's drawings so,

00:19:28.900 --> 00:19:30.790
and here we have the
original still today

00:19:30.790 --> 00:19:33.400
in the Naval Archeological
Museum,

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:34.700
and you can check this out,

00:19:34.700 --> 00:19:37.610
even down to this tongue
sticking out, right,

00:19:37.610 --> 00:19:40.840
Brumidi has based
this on this drawing.

00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:43.930
Right? Brumidi, we can't
guarantee, would know this

00:19:43.930 --> 00:19:46.600
but we can see that he was
looking at Wilhelm Zahn

00:19:46.600 --> 00:19:49.910
and just another
attendant flanking Neptune.

00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:53.630
You can see here, okay, so
it was Europa and the bull

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:56.590
but he changed the
bull into a hippocamp

00:19:56.590 --> 00:19:58.440
and then the horse
turned his head away

00:19:58.440 --> 00:20:02.450
because it was this sort of
romantic myth behind [laughter].

00:20:02.450 --> 00:20:03.940
So, but you can see, right?

00:20:03.940 --> 00:20:07.700
You believe me that Brumidi was
actually using Wilhelm Zahn's

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:09.090
drawings, right?

00:20:09.090 --> 00:20:15.750
Okay, so how did Brumidi
get a hold of this book

00:20:15.750 --> 00:20:23.420
and the real question is could
these books be the exact copies

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:25.690
that Zahn was using?

00:20:25.690 --> 00:20:29.670
And he had the commission
for this room in 1856

00:20:29.670 --> 00:20:33.650
and he completed it in 1958.

00:20:33.650 --> 00:20:36.250
So the hunt was on.

00:20:36.250 --> 00:20:39.780
Here I am when I first
met Michael and the books

00:20:39.780 --> 00:20:42.110
by Wilhelm Zahn, right?

00:20:42.110 --> 00:20:44.420
And I wanted to try
to figure out whether

00:20:44.420 --> 00:20:46.870
or not Brumidi could've
used these.

00:20:46.870 --> 00:20:50.080
And this is one of the funniest
stories of this whole mystery.

00:20:50.080 --> 00:20:52.250
I mean, I'm an archeologist
and an art historian

00:20:52.250 --> 00:20:53.550
and I've worked in museums.

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:55.530
You know, I've been a
visiting assistant curator here

00:20:55.530 --> 00:20:56.830
and blah, blah, blah.

00:20:56.830 --> 00:20:58.680
So I turned to Michael
when I got a hold

00:20:58.680 --> 00:21:00.470
of these books finally
and I said,

00:21:00.470 --> 00:21:02.260
"Could I see your
file on these books?"

00:21:02.260 --> 00:21:05.020
And he looked at me and he
said, "File on the books?"

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:06.320
And I said, "Well, yeah.

00:21:06.320 --> 00:21:07.620
Where have these things been?"

00:21:07.620 --> 00:21:08.920
Like, I don't know,
where did you get them,

00:21:08.920 --> 00:21:10.220
when did you get them,
who's used them?"

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:13.910
And he said, "We don't
keep files like that."

00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:15.210
And I thought, what do you mean?

00:21:15.210 --> 00:21:18.330
Because in a museum every object
that walks in the building

00:21:18.330 --> 00:21:20.350
and belongs to your collection
has a file and you know

00:21:20.350 --> 00:21:22.740
where it's been every second
of every day basically.

00:21:22.740 --> 00:21:26.290
And he said, "We have a
lot of books like this."

00:21:26.290 --> 00:21:29.170
So I was like, right,
okay, I'm going to have

00:21:29.170 --> 00:21:33.820
to reconstruct the
provenience of this book.

00:21:33.820 --> 00:21:36.710
So there were several
things that were helpful

00:21:36.710 --> 00:21:38.950
like when I began
sleuthing together, right?

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:44.600
It turns out that there is
a blind stamp in the front,

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:49.560
on the frontis page
of both of these books

00:21:49.560 --> 00:21:52.020
and that blind stamp
is actually tied

00:21:52.020 --> 00:21:54.780
to the first international
copyright law.

00:21:54.780 --> 00:21:56.080
This is all very exciting.

00:21:56.080 --> 00:22:03.740
Because you can see it says
Vertrag Vom 13 Mai 1846.

00:22:03.740 --> 00:22:09.040
So in 1846 on the 13tth

00:22:09.040 --> 00:22:12.830
of May there was a convention
established between Prussia

00:22:12.830 --> 00:22:16.720
and Britain that had
to do with the export

00:22:16.720 --> 00:22:19.120
of books and paying taxes.

00:22:19.120 --> 00:22:23.210
And so if a book was meant to
be exported to Britain it had

00:22:23.210 --> 00:22:28.810
to have this kind of stamp on
it and so we know, therefore,

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:31.090
that the book, which
incidentally was printed

00:22:31.090 --> 00:22:34.580
in Berlin by a very famous
publisher, Gaylord [inaudible]

00:22:34.580 --> 00:22:39.680
and the Volume One
was printed in 1829,

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:43.650
Volume Two that you
see there 1841 to 44,

00:22:43.650 --> 00:22:47.460
Volume Three we don't have
because it was after Brumidi

00:22:47.460 --> 00:22:54.330
and he didn't use it, but
that was 1852 to 1859.

00:22:54.330 --> 00:22:58.490
So we know that the same
Volume One, at least,

00:22:58.490 --> 00:23:03.030
was printed in 1829 and it had

00:23:03.030 --> 00:23:08.140
to have left Germany [inaudible]
term after September 1st,

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:11.920
when this went into
effect, of 1846.

00:23:11.920 --> 00:23:13.220
Okay, that's good, right?

00:23:13.220 --> 00:23:16.540
So we kind of have an idea
of when the book left.

00:23:16.540 --> 00:23:17.840
We know that it must've gone

00:23:17.840 --> 00:23:20.620
to Britain otherwise it wouldn't
have had that stamp in it.

00:23:20.620 --> 00:23:22.800
But Michael said, yeah,
not to worry there are tons

00:23:22.800 --> 00:23:25.640
of book sellers, right,
selling to America in Britain

00:23:25.640 --> 00:23:28.670
so that's cool, that
could've taken that path.

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:32.600
There's also this stamp on
this book stamp of the Library

00:23:32.600 --> 00:23:34.340
of Congress and it turns

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:40.030
out that this was a common stamp
used in the mid 19th century

00:23:40.030 --> 00:23:44.990
and actually the
archivist, Cheryl,

00:23:44.990 --> 00:23:48.230
told me one of the dead
ringers here said this is listed

00:23:48.230 --> 00:23:51.350
as Library of Congress
City of Washington,

00:23:51.350 --> 00:23:55.270
as opposed to Washington
D.C., that the name tends

00:23:55.270 --> 00:23:57.570
to change after the Civil War.

00:23:57.570 --> 00:24:01.980
Okay? So that was good but
here is the dead ringer.

00:24:01.980 --> 00:24:04.620
Then I began searching
through published catalogues

00:24:04.620 --> 00:24:08.500
of the Library of Congress to
try to determine if I could see

00:24:08.500 --> 00:24:11.480
when we acquired
this book, right?

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:13.720
And that also required
Michael's help

00:24:13.720 --> 00:24:18.330
because although the HathiTrust
has a lot of the catalogues,

00:24:18.330 --> 00:24:20.910
the published catalogues of
the Library of Congress online.

00:24:20.910 --> 00:24:23.290
They didn't have
anything between 1830

00:24:23.290 --> 00:24:27.750
and like 1850-something
and so, after my time,

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:29.460
like 1859 or something.

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:30.760
I was like, "I have this gap,

00:24:30.760 --> 00:24:32.950
Michael do you have your
catalogue from 18," you know.

00:24:32.950 --> 00:24:36.170
And so I looked through all
the catalogues and, behold,

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:40.070
we can see that in 1849, here's
the first record of the Library

00:24:40.070 --> 00:24:42.800
of Congress's ownership
of Zahn's publication.

00:24:42.800 --> 00:24:45.280
And we have Volumes
One and Two here,

00:24:45.280 --> 00:24:48.460
note that they're classified
under gardening, painting,

00:24:48.460 --> 00:24:51.320
et cetera, according
to Jefferson's category

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:53.010
of imagination [inaudible].

00:24:53.010 --> 00:24:56.250
I thought that was very
funny [inaudible], et cetera.

00:24:56.250 --> 00:24:57.550
But there they are.

00:24:57.550 --> 00:25:02.370
So we know that they made their
way here by 1849 and that's

00:25:02.370 --> 00:25:07.910
in plenty of time for our
hero to consult them in 1854

00:25:07.910 --> 00:25:10.420
or 56, so that's exciting.

00:25:10.420 --> 00:25:11.720
So that's good.

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:15.880
So I think I can make
a pretty sound argument

00:25:15.880 --> 00:25:18.940
that he could've used
these exact volumes.

00:25:18.940 --> 00:25:22.510
But then I decided to
try going a step further.

00:25:22.510 --> 00:25:25.430
So it turns out that
Montgomery Meigs, who was kind

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:29.570
of Brumidi's patron if
you will, kept a journal.

00:25:29.570 --> 00:25:32.230
Fortunately, I mean,
and he wrote

00:25:32.230 --> 00:25:33.640
down every matter of detail.

00:25:33.640 --> 00:25:35.750
It was unbelievable.

00:25:35.750 --> 00:25:37.490
Well, it's only unbelievable
if you read

00:25:37.490 --> 00:25:39.810
if in the transcribed
version because it turns

00:25:39.810 --> 00:25:44.630
out that the guy wrote in this
thing called Pittman shorthand.

00:25:44.630 --> 00:25:48.610
[inaudible] anyone ever tried
to read Pittman shorthand?

00:25:48.610 --> 00:25:52.590
So, okay, my daughter is taking
Arabic and you saw that some

00:25:52.590 --> 00:25:53.890
of my research is in Jordan.

00:25:53.890 --> 00:25:56.270
It's like scarier than Arabic.

00:25:56.270 --> 00:25:57.570
Here, look [laughter].

00:25:57.570 --> 00:26:02.200
Even more impenetrable
to me than Arabic.

00:26:02.200 --> 00:26:06.300
So I went over to Madison
and I met with Jeff Flannery

00:26:06.300 --> 00:26:09.890
and he got the journal out
for me and we tried to look

00:26:09.890 --> 00:26:12.410
at it because, see, what
happened was in 2000

00:26:12.410 --> 00:26:14.900
for the anniversary of
the Capitol Building,

00:26:14.900 --> 00:26:16.640
they hired this incredible
person

00:26:16.640 --> 00:26:18.760
who could still read
Pittman shorthand

00:26:18.760 --> 00:26:23.450
to transcribe the diaries
of Montgomery Meigs,

00:26:23.450 --> 00:26:24.850
especially the ones
that had to do

00:26:24.850 --> 00:26:26.550
with the Capitol
Building, right?

00:26:26.550 --> 00:26:31.080
So I had this searchable
pdf and I could see,

00:26:31.080 --> 00:26:36.060
in English you know
[laughter], that I could see

00:26:36.060 --> 00:26:41.300
that on June 22nd, 1858,
when my room is completed,

00:26:41.300 --> 00:26:43.410
Brumidi is all done
with the room,

00:26:43.410 --> 00:26:46.630
Meigs is in there admiring
a room and he says,

00:26:46.630 --> 00:26:51.270
"The Pompeiian rooms are better
than the examples from Pompeii

00:26:51.270 --> 00:26:55.630
in the book of blank
and the other styles are

00:26:55.630 --> 00:26:59.270
as well represented as in
any of the plates given

00:26:59.270 --> 00:27:03.690
in any of these books."

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:08.810
Well, what happened was our
transcriber was going along

00:27:08.810 --> 00:27:14.080
doing his thing transcribing
but he doesn't know names

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:16.730
like [inaudible], Gell,
Zahn, Niccolini, [inaudible],

00:27:16.730 --> 00:27:19.530
he doesn't know those names.

00:27:19.530 --> 00:27:24.640
So he came across a word
that was a proper name

00:27:24.640 --> 00:27:29.250
that he didn't know
and he left it blank.

00:27:29.250 --> 00:27:32.620
And there are blanks like this
throughout the transcription.

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:34.310
You can understand, right?

00:27:34.310 --> 00:27:38.530
It's hard to keep up
with Montgomery Meigs.

00:27:38.530 --> 00:27:42.330
So Jeff and I thought maybe
we could look at the diary

00:27:42.330 --> 00:27:44.140
and we could figure this out.

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:51.470
And then we looked at the
diary and we were like, yeah,

00:27:51.470 --> 00:27:54.440
you pretty much need to
read Pittman shorthand

00:27:54.440 --> 00:27:55.740
to figure that out.

00:27:55.740 --> 00:27:58.040
So then I met Michelle
Krowl and she said, "Well,

00:27:58.040 --> 00:28:03.350
I have an elderly woman who
used to do some things for us

00:28:03.350 --> 00:28:06.920
who lives in Quincy,
Massachusetts.

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:09.200
Here's her email address."

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:13.730
So I emailed her
and she was amazing.

00:28:13.730 --> 00:28:17.880
She emailed me back.

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:23.100
I sent her color
printouts of these images

00:28:23.100 --> 00:28:30.930
with stickies everywhere
and I could tell that this,

00:28:30.930 --> 00:28:37.400
because it's the last sentence
of the June 22nd journal entry

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:42.030
and this is the last sentence
because there's an x here

00:28:42.030 --> 00:28:47.370
that means the end of the
sentence and here's 23rd

00:28:47.370 --> 00:28:52.930
for the start of the next
journal entry, right?

00:28:52.930 --> 00:28:55.760
So I could see there's the
end of the previous sentence.

00:28:55.760 --> 00:29:01.870
So I knew it was this sentence
and I could kind of see

00:29:01.870 --> 00:29:04.600
that some of the words
were being repeated,

00:29:04.600 --> 00:29:06.200
Pompeii or Pompeiian.

00:29:06.200 --> 00:29:13.450
So I was able to narrow it
down and she read it for me

00:29:13.450 --> 00:29:15.070
and she said, "Hey, guess what?

00:29:15.070 --> 00:29:18.950
There's your word and it says,"

