00:29:58.990 --> 00:30:00.290
So how do they know to buy these
volumes by Wilhelm Zahn, right?

00:30:00.290 --> 00:30:01.590
And so what I thought I should
do is put this in a little bit

00:30:01.590 --> 00:30:02.890
of a context of the history
of excavations of Pompeii.

00:30:02.890 --> 00:30:04.190
So here's a map of Pompeii and
I don't know if you can sort

00:30:04.190 --> 00:30:05.490
of read this from where you're
sitting but it has the dates

00:30:05.490 --> 00:30:06.790
of all the excavations
of the city.

00:30:06.790 --> 00:30:08.090
And you can see that we are
sort of, we're, so the House

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:09.390
of the Ship is discovered
in 1826

00:30:09.390 --> 00:30:10.690
and that's this blue
part, right?

00:30:10.690 --> 00:30:11.990
And Brumidi is alive
and sort of learning

00:30:11.990 --> 00:30:15.640
to be an artist during the
largest excavation campaign

00:30:15.640 --> 00:30:20.480
to date, which occurred
between 1850 and 1860, right?

00:30:20.480 --> 00:30:23.720
I mean, Pompeii gets
discovered in 1748,

00:30:23.720 --> 00:30:27.490
initially they thought it was
actually another little town,

00:30:27.490 --> 00:30:28.790
[inaudible].

00:30:28.790 --> 00:30:30.090
So it took them a while to
figure out where they were

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:35.190
and these first excavations,
which you can see here,

00:30:35.190 --> 00:30:38.350
it's a light grey but it doesn't
show up very well on the screen,

00:30:38.350 --> 00:30:41.970
were in this theater
area triangular forum

00:30:41.970 --> 00:30:46.020
and a little piece up here but
then there was a second wave

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:54.990
of excavations in 1806 to
1815, so-called French decade.

00:30:54.990 --> 00:31:00.340
But then the Bourbon
Restoration from 1850 to 1860 is

00:31:00.340 --> 00:31:03.070
when there's really the
largest scale excavations

00:31:03.070 --> 00:31:04.650
that had ever been
conducted at the site.

00:31:04.650 --> 00:31:08.930
And this is the lifetime
of Brumidi, right?

00:31:08.930 --> 00:31:11.770
And the other thing that's
important for you to know,

00:31:11.770 --> 00:31:14.700
just here's a little marker
to show you where that House

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:16.800
of the Ship is located, right?

00:31:16.800 --> 00:31:21.280
So it was excavated in three
different years and our room

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:25.530
with its wall painting
is found in 1826.

00:31:25.530 --> 00:31:31.820
So this means that this is also
the era of huge publication

00:31:31.820 --> 00:31:34.800
of the site of Pompeii.

00:31:34.800 --> 00:31:42.180
And this is the time when all
sorts of, you know, artists

00:31:42.180 --> 00:31:48.550
and architects and elites were
going to the Bay of Naples area

00:31:48.550 --> 00:31:50.460
and looking at the discoveries

00:31:50.460 --> 00:31:52.770
that were being made
before their very eyes

00:31:52.770 --> 00:31:54.730
at Pompeii, right?

00:31:54.730 --> 00:31:57.790
So this is the, you know, still
the era of the grand tour.

00:31:57.790 --> 00:31:59.530
I don't know if you've
heard of the grand tour.

00:31:59.530 --> 00:32:05.970
And so here are some examples
of the kinds of publications

00:32:05.970 --> 00:32:09.050
that were beginning
to appear, right?

00:32:09.050 --> 00:32:11.100
And it's just three
of the most important

00:32:11.100 --> 00:32:12.970
and well known publications

00:32:12.970 --> 00:32:15.650
from the first half
of the 19th century.

00:32:15.650 --> 00:32:16.950
So we have William Gell,

00:32:16.950 --> 00:32:19.450
who writes something called
Pompeiana and it's published

00:32:19.450 --> 00:32:22.950
between 1817 and 1832.

00:32:22.950 --> 00:32:27.070
French, Francois Mazois
[inaudible] Pompeii from 1824

00:32:27.070 --> 00:32:31.030
to 1838, and then the
famous Niccolini brothers,

00:32:31.030 --> 00:32:35.410
Fausto and Felice
Niccolini in 1854.

00:32:35.410 --> 00:32:39.270
And what I wanted you to see was

00:32:39.270 --> 00:32:43.450
that these volumes are
very similar to one another

00:32:43.450 --> 00:32:50.360
because while they do have some
plates in them and some drawings

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:54.510
and some of them are these
very alluring reconstructions

00:32:54.510 --> 00:32:57.810
that get populated by
ancients, you know.

00:32:57.810 --> 00:33:00.950
So you can, they sort of
reconstruct the houses

00:33:00.950 --> 00:33:05.350
that have been excavated and
they install Romans in them,

00:33:05.350 --> 00:33:08.210
you know, swishing around
the atrium or whatever.

00:33:08.210 --> 00:33:12.250
Most of what's in
these volumes is

00:33:12.250 --> 00:33:15.180
that [laughter] narrative
discussion

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:17.200
of what they are discovering.

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:21.650
Very helpful, extremely
important but as I began

00:33:21.650 --> 00:33:25.140
to dabble in 19th century
publications from the University

00:33:25.140 --> 00:33:27.490
of Heidelberg and the
Getty Research Institute,

00:33:27.490 --> 00:33:30.120
thank God for digitization
of these things,

00:33:30.120 --> 00:33:32.280
and then I was looking at these,

00:33:32.280 --> 00:33:36.750
I thought Zahn doesn't
look like these guys.

00:33:36.750 --> 00:33:38.790
He's different, right?

00:33:38.790 --> 00:33:43.550
And in fact, Zahn is
different in a lot of ways

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:48.630
and so here's just the frontis
from Volume One that you can see

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:51.330
on the screen and we could
look at later if you wanted.

00:33:51.330 --> 00:33:52.860
So how is Zahn different?

00:33:52.860 --> 00:33:56.280
First of all, Zahn
is bilingual, right?

00:33:56.280 --> 00:33:58.220
So those others that I
had shown you, you know,

00:33:58.220 --> 00:34:00.910
one was by a British guy,
one was by a French guy,

00:34:00.910 --> 00:34:02.250
the Niccolini brothers
are Italian,

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:05.250
and they're in their
respective languages, right?

00:34:05.250 --> 00:34:09.160
We are bilingual, we're
in German and in French

00:34:09.160 --> 00:34:14.110
and the real difference is these
are really virtually all images.

00:34:14.110 --> 00:34:21.040
He has one page of "texts" that
are mini catalogue entries.

00:34:21.040 --> 00:34:24.760
So you have some minimal
information about the background

00:34:24.760 --> 00:34:27.890
for each image, that
appears at the front,

00:34:27.890 --> 00:34:30.620
and then there are a
bunch of plates in between

00:34:30.620 --> 00:34:32.260
and then there's
another set of 10

00:34:32.260 --> 00:34:34.590
and a bunch of plates
in between.

00:34:34.590 --> 00:34:39.190
So there's only one
page of text per folio.

00:34:39.190 --> 00:34:43.230
It is not at all a narrative
in any way, shape, or form.

00:34:43.230 --> 00:34:45.580
And the other thing
that's radically different

00:34:45.580 --> 00:34:47.630
about these is the color.

00:34:47.630 --> 00:34:50.060
Okay? And you can see that
as you look at the table

00:34:50.060 --> 00:34:51.420
and you can see that here.

00:34:51.420 --> 00:34:55.830
And it really makes Zahn,
oops, where's my color?

00:34:55.830 --> 00:35:00.110
There you go, it really
makes Zahn stand out, right?

00:35:00.110 --> 00:35:03.850
So who was this guy and, you
know, I figured I'm going

00:35:03.850 --> 00:35:06.360
to have to put this guy
on the map a little bit

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:10.200
for the general discussion.

00:35:10.200 --> 00:35:15.390
Certainly, specialists who
work with this era know

00:35:15.390 --> 00:35:16.890
about him but, you know,

00:35:16.890 --> 00:35:19.750
people who are just general
Roman art historians seem

00:35:19.750 --> 00:35:21.480
to not have heard of him.

00:35:21.480 --> 00:35:24.400
So he was a German
decorative painter.

00:35:24.400 --> 00:35:29.300
He was born in 1800 and he
trained at the Casell Academy

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:33.770
of Fine Arts, after which he
went to Paris for about a year

00:35:33.770 --> 00:35:37.040
and hung out with Antione
[inaudible] very famous

00:35:37.040 --> 00:35:39.380
neoclassical painter.

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:48.720
And then Wilhelm Zahn lived in
Pompeii from 1824 or 25 to 1829

00:35:48.720 --> 00:35:51.530
and again from 1830 to 1840.

00:35:51.530 --> 00:35:53.540
And he was just hanging

00:35:53.540 --> 00:35:57.470
around while things were being
discovered and drawing them.

00:35:57.470 --> 00:36:02.080
Okay? And he says in his
introduction that his goal

00:36:02.080 --> 00:36:05.710
at Pompeii was "to
copy as faithfully

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:10.840
as possible ancient paintings
and to reproduce the original

00:36:10.840 --> 00:36:14.850
with the accuracy
that science demands".

00:36:14.850 --> 00:36:18.500
So he's responsible not
only for this set of, well,

00:36:18.500 --> 00:36:21.940
you have two volumes here
but there is a third one,

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:27.880
but he also published many other
things, several other volumes.

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:33.730
And he is an extraordinary
character in many ways.

00:36:33.730 --> 00:36:38.900
He was befriended by
Goethe in 1829 and, in fact,

00:36:38.900 --> 00:36:45.660
when Zahn returned to Berlin
for this break in between,

00:36:45.660 --> 00:36:49.320
he goes to Goethe and Goethe
immediately befriends him

00:36:49.320 --> 00:36:52.970
and he spends weeks at a time
with Goethe and gets introduced

00:36:52.970 --> 00:36:57.170
to all kinds of important
people like, you know,

00:36:57.170 --> 00:37:00.640
the future King of Prussia.

00:37:00.640 --> 00:37:06.910
And he is also extremely
important

00:37:06.910 --> 00:37:11.450
because he is a major
figure in the development

00:37:11.450 --> 00:37:15.340
of color lithography, which
I had no idea until recently.

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:17.370
I mean, this is all a
whole new world to me.

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:19.570
I moved to the 19th century,
little did I know how big

00:37:19.570 --> 00:37:21.730
that move was going
to be, right?

00:37:21.730 --> 00:37:27.660
And so he really used the
publication of these volumes

00:37:27.660 --> 00:37:32.110
to push forward the
technology of lithography

00:37:32.110 --> 00:37:36.540
and chromolithography
and apparently you can,

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:39.910
now I'm not trained to see
this so I can't point this out

00:37:39.910 --> 00:37:41.210
and I'm sorry for that,

00:37:41.210 --> 00:37:44.820
but apparently you can see
him develop the technology

00:37:44.820 --> 00:37:49.960
from volume to volume to
volume, which is fascinating.

00:37:49.960 --> 00:37:54.130
This was also a massive
effort and expense.

00:37:54.130 --> 00:37:57.220
I read that it turns
out that Gerheimer,

00:37:57.220 --> 00:38:02.480
who was a pretty well known,
large publisher in Berlin,

00:38:02.480 --> 00:38:05.140
when he agreed to
publish Volume One,

00:38:05.140 --> 00:38:07.610
this wasn't originally
conceived as a three-volume set,

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:09.030
it was just going
to be one volume,

00:38:09.030 --> 00:38:10.330
when he originally agreed

00:38:10.330 --> 00:38:15.120
to publish Volume One he
withheld the payment from Zahn

00:38:15.120 --> 00:38:18.980
until he could see that it was a
financially successful endeavor.

00:38:18.980 --> 00:38:23.700
And so once he saw that people
were buying these he paid Zahn

00:38:23.700 --> 00:38:26.990
and eventually Zahn came
back and did Volume Two

00:38:26.990 --> 00:38:28.800
and then Volume Three.

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:33.560
But we have some descriptions
by Zahn himself, which we know

00:38:33.560 --> 00:38:36.910
about because Goethe includes
them in a review he does

00:38:36.910 --> 00:38:42.070
of Zahn's Volume One, in
which Zahn talks about setting

00:38:42.070 --> 00:38:45.700
up the lithography workshop
because this didn't exist.

00:38:45.700 --> 00:38:49.800
And talking about 20 printers
and four to five artists

00:38:49.800 --> 00:38:52.590
and it was incredible.

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:57.820
Now, there are some
other interesting things

00:38:57.820 --> 00:39:00.220
that I just want to point
out but I am going to wrap it

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:02.090
up so I don't keep people
too long and I can try

00:39:02.090 --> 00:39:07.140
to answer questions, and that is
this is only a connection I made

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:11.360
just recently so Zahn talks
about being most proud

00:39:11.360 --> 00:39:14.730
of some specific plates in each
of the volumes that he's done

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:18.400
in terms of the challenge
that it was to produce them

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:22.500
and get the color just right and
things, and this is one of them.

00:39:22.500 --> 00:39:26.080
This is plate 99
from Volume One.

00:39:26.080 --> 00:39:31.950
And it turns out that
that's blue, right?

00:39:31.950 --> 00:39:36.810
Because we have blue in our room

00:39:36.810 --> 00:39:39.290
and everybody is always
saying 'oh it's American blue,

00:39:39.290 --> 00:39:42.380
you know, Brumidi just
Americanized the background',

00:39:42.380 --> 00:39:44.230
he took the black, right,

00:39:44.230 --> 00:39:48.230
he took away the black Pompeiian
background and he made it blue.

00:39:48.230 --> 00:39:51.020
And we actually have
a water color study

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:53.700
in which he also tried
out a red background.

00:39:53.700 --> 00:39:57.830
But I never, I mean, I was
always thinking it's just sort

00:39:57.830 --> 00:40:00.570
of American blue
background, right?

00:40:00.570 --> 00:40:04.550
Well now, I'm pretty convinced
that he picked this blue

00:40:04.550 --> 00:40:09.680
up from actual Pompeiian wall
paintings that he had seen.

00:40:09.680 --> 00:40:13.510
And there's a whole debate
actually about this plate

00:40:13.510 --> 00:40:15.120
that I'm currently
reading about,

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:18.390
because we not only have
Zahn's depiction of it

00:40:18.390 --> 00:40:22.890
but have a 19th century
wash of it

00:40:22.890 --> 00:40:25.350
and the blues are
slightly different

00:40:25.350 --> 00:40:29.820
and the painted one is much
closer to our blue in the room.

00:40:29.820 --> 00:40:31.300
So it's just fascinating
to look at that.

00:40:31.300 --> 00:40:33.720
But anyway, so that's one thing.

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:37.370
Another thing that I'm
looking into is I wonder

00:40:37.370 --> 00:40:43.630
if Brumidi actually
knew Wilhelm Zahn.

00:40:43.630 --> 00:40:46.470
If you look at their
lives, so firs to fall,

00:40:46.470 --> 00:40:48.440
they're both artists, right?

00:40:48.440 --> 00:40:53.190
And there are areas
that are listed in red

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:55.400
where they overlap, right?

00:40:55.400 --> 00:40:59.390
And so Zahn is known
to have stopped in Rome

00:40:59.390 --> 00:41:01.720
for a bit before he
went down to Pompeii.

00:41:01.720 --> 00:41:05.150
He came from Paris, stopped
in Rome, and went to Pompeii.

00:41:05.150 --> 00:41:06.820
And so I'm in touch

00:41:06.820 --> 00:41:10.310
with a former U.S. Capitol
Historical Society fellow

00:41:10.310 --> 00:41:14.880
who has worked before in
the archives of the Academy

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:16.510
of de San Luca, the
famous art school

00:41:16.510 --> 00:41:19.480
where Brumidi was trained,
and would know this, you know,

00:41:19.480 --> 00:41:21.660
